I reviewed it more closely, and the default for insert is definitely `false` but is `1` for count (when `insert=true` is passed)

Though I do see there's actually another bug underneath this. Count doesn't really have a default when insert is false (insert's default) and will produce multiple `NaN`s in spliceRows.

```javascript
  duplicateRow(rowNum, count, insert = false) {
    // create count duplicates of rowNum
    // either inserting new or overwriting existing rows

    const rSrc = this._rows[rowNum - 1];
    const inserts = new Array(count).fill(rSrc.values);            //new Array(undefined).fill('x') === ['x']
    this.spliceRows(rowNum + 1, insert ? 0 : count, ...inserts);   //insert=false -> undefined
   // ...
  }

  spliceRows(start, count, ...inserts) {
    const nKeep = start + count;                                   // start + undefined === NaN
    const nInserts = inserts.length;
    const nExpand = nInserts - count;                              // nInserts - undefined === NaN
```

How does making a PR to update the code to match the docs sound? Assign the default of insert to true instead of false (which seems to be the more logical one?) and also adding an `if (count === undefined){ count = 1; }` at the start of duplicateRow?
